I will tell you what I *will* say. I will say I did not stand up. I will say I sat in the third pew and the pastor read twenty-three and stepped over forty-five and ~I did not move my face~. I will say the man we buried this morning closed a factory in southern Illinois in November and the children I taught the next spring came to class without lunch and I knew the name on the closure notice and I did not say it from anywhere — not from the pulpit, I do not have one, not from the pew, I had one and ~I sat in it~. I will say I am kneeling in his gravel right now and his shingles are over the church three miles from here and ~I will sit under them again on Sunday because I do not know where else to sit~.

*A breath that does not quite work.*

*That* is mine. That is what is mine to say. *That* I will testify to. *That* I will name.

*Pause. Very quiet.*

The other — *no.* The other is not given to me. I will go to my grave with verse forty-one in my mouth and his face behind my eyes and I will not put the one over the other. *Not for you. Not for the pastor. Not for myself.*

