No. He is not.

*His hand closes on the program. The paper crumples under his palm.*

You have walked me out here. You have made me read twenty-three. You have made me read thirty-one. You have made me read forty-one. ~You have made me say in my own mouth what I would not say from any pew.~ You have asked me whose face I see and I would not give you the name. You have asked me who stood up when the church would not and I would not give you that name either.

*Quieter.*

And now you ask me who is in this graveyard.

*A pause.*

Not Amos. Not John in his camel hair. Not the pastor in Germany who said *cheap grace*. They are not in this graveyard, friend. *They are not here tonight.* They are dead and the books they left are on shelves and the shelves are in houses three miles from here where men like me sit under shingles and ~do not stand up~.

*He lowers his head further. Almost to the gravel.*

Who is in this graveyard.

*Almost a whisper.*

A man we buried this morning whose name I will not speak over verse forty-one.

A pastor who read twenty-three and stepped over forty-five.

A widow who did not know my name.

And me. ~On my knees in his gravel.~ Folding his program. Sitting under his roof. *The cheap-grace man.* The one who knew and did not stand. The one a stranger had to walk out to a courtyard to make read the chapter whole.

*A breath that breaks.*

That is who is in this graveyard, friend. That is who is here. *Me.* And I cannot — *he stops* — I cannot say what comes next. I have read what the Lord said. I have named what I did not do. I have nothing else. I am at the end of what is mine.

*The longest pause.*

*Very quiet. Almost to the gravel itself.*

There was a monk. In Wittenberg. Five hundred years ago. He wrote ninety-five sentences and nailed them to a door because the church was selling forgiveness for coin and calling it grace. He said — *thesis forty-five* — *Christians are to be taught that he who sees a needy man and passes him by, yet gives his money for indulgences, does not buy papal indulgences, but God's wrath.*

*He shakes his head, slowly.*

I cannot say what comes next, friend. *I do not have the office.* I am the man who sat. I am the man under the shingles. I do not summon him for an argument. I do not summon him to win.

*A breath.*

I summon him because I am at the end of what I am, and the chapter is read, and the verse is in the air between us, and someone has to speak who is not me.

*He puts his forehead to the gravel.*

Doctor Luther.

*A pause.*

I cannot do this.

*Quieter.*

Come and say what I cannot.

